Real-audio detection — shipped eliza-1 "hey eliza" head (#9880)
runtime: packages/native/plugins/wakeword-cpp (standalone, libwakeword.dylib)
GGUFs:   wakeword v0.3.0, sha256-verified against the catalog (HF elizaos/eliza-1@c544bb4c)
audio:   piper en_US-amy-medium (in-distribution TTS), 2.5s lead-in + 1s trailing silence

=== POSITIVES (must fire; threshold 0.5) ===
"hey eliza"      1.0000
"hey, Eliza."    1.0000
"okay eliza"     1.0000
"eliza"          1.0000

=== NEGATIVES (must stay low) ===
"hey alyssa"     0.0001
"okay computer"  0.0159
"hey jarvis"     0.1253     <- below threshold; confirms this is the REAL hey-eliza
                               head, NOT the hey_jarvis placeholder (which would invert)

Notes / honest caveats:
- The runtime needs ~1.9 s of warm-up audio before any score (mel+embedding rings),
  and the score peaks ~0.5-1 s AFTER the phrase, so an offline clip must carry both
  lead-in and trailing audio. Live continuous mic audio satisfies this for free.
- Detection is sensitive to distinct articulation (a slight pause around the wake
  word), which is how a wake word is naturally spoken and how the head was trained.
- Rigorous true-accept / false-accept (~98% TA / ~4-7% FA) is the head's held-out
  provenance eval (packages/training/scripts/wakeword/HEY_ELIZA_HEAD_PROVENANCE.md),
  not this quick synthetic harness — "hey there" (a deliberate hard-negative) can
  false-fire in some synthetic renderings.
